That returning clause makes sense only inside a pl/sql block, and not in some SQL statement sent from Java or some other client. That is why it doesn&#39;t work.
A pl/sql block means basically somethign like below:

    Declare 
      /* variable declarations as needed*/
      v_ret number;
    begin
      /* several SQL statements as needed*/
      insert into x_table (... /* list of columns*/
      ) values (
      /* values to insert*/&#39;
      x_id
      ...
      ) returning x_id into v_ret;     
    end;

I never recall having used returning with an insert select. Why? Because that select may possibly return no rows whatsoever or may return several rows. How could that work then with a simple variable? 
In case a DML (could be insert select or could be even an update or delete) may affect several rows you should use returning bulk collect, like in the example at https://doyensys.com/blogs/returning-clause-with-bulk-collect/

